^-{ The Common Hand Evaluation Methods }
^-|FP||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|There are literally billions of bridge hands. But, there are only 38 legal bids. So you cannot describe every possible hand with the available bids. Therefore, what you do is classify a specific hand into a larger group. Hand evaluation is concerned with deciding what group a particular hand belongs to. I will describe 3 common methods for evaluating a hand.|
PG| ***** 89 ***** |


HT|j|cs|6|fp|3|at|
^-{ Classic Hand Evaluation }
^-|FP||AT|^B@2^Y@3Those new to bridge should start with classic hand evaluation. It is easy to learn and reasonably accurate. I have used it quite successfully for many years, and it works well. |
PG| ***** 90 ***** |


AT|

The first thing you do is count your High Card Points (HCP) using what is known as the classic Work method (the method was invented by Milton Work). You count 4 points for an Ace, 3 for a King, 2 for a Queen, and 1 for a Jack. You then add points for distribution. You add 1 point for each doubleton, 2 points for each singleton, and 3 points for each void. |
PG| ***** 91 ***** |


AT|

Finally, you make adjustments for dubious short suits. You subtract one point for a singleton King, Queen, or Jack. You also subtract one point for a doubleton Queen or Jack. The reasoning behind this is that you may be forced to prematurely play honors in short suits, and therefore they are worth less than if they were in a longer suit. |
PG| ***** 92 ***** |


NT||
HT|e|cs|6|fp|3|at|^-{Classic Hand Evaluation}
^-|FP||AT|^B@2^Y@3Some teachers feel you should count length rather than shortness for distribution. Using this method, you add 1 point for each card above 4 in a suit. Hence, you add 1 point for a 5 card suit, 2 points for a 6 card suit, and so forth. |
PG| ***** 93 ***** |


AT|

Their argument is that until you find a fit, shortness does not help. For the most part, the two methods are equivalent. However, I feel the shortness method is slightly more accurate. For example, a 5-4-3-1 hand is worth more than a 5-3-3-2 hand. However, using the length method, both hands would only add 1 point for distribution. But using the shortness method, you would add 2 points for the 5-4-3-1 hand but only 1 point for length for the 5-3-3-2 hand; I think this is more realistic. However, if you prefer the length method for counting distribution, that is fine.|
PG| ***** 94 ***** |


