Many good players are very enthusiastic about using Losing Trick Count. It is easy to learn. However, I do not share their enthusiasm. For distributional hands, it is not bad, but it is less accurate for flatter hands. And, I think it has some major flaws. For example, Qxx and Axx are both one loser suits, but clearly Axx is much better. To be fair, the Klinger book talks about adjustments to take care of some of these problems. The one place I do use LTC is when I have a borderline bidding decision. If LTC indicates I should make the more aggressive bid, then I will do so.|
