As to 4th suit forcing. 4th suit forcing is a convention that only applies when opener bids one suit, responder bids another suit, and opener rebids a third suit. That leaves only one unbid suit. If responder bids the remaining unbid suit (the "fourth suit"), that is the 4th suit forcing convention if you play it. It simply establishes a game force, is completely artificial, and says nothing about the fourth suit. Responder will clarify why he or she bid the 4th suit on the next bid. Opener should try and  bid NT (but only with a stopper in the 4th suit, as responder is not guaranteeing a stopper in the fourth suit) or raise responder's first suit with 3 card support. If opener cannot do that, he or she must rebid one of their suits.|
PG| ***** 144 ***** |


AT|

New minor forcing is a very specific convention that only applies when opener rebids 1NT or 2NT. It does not apply on any other auction (e.g. 1D-1H-1S-2C is fourth suit forcing, not new minor forcing; also 1S-2D-2S-3C is natural, not new minor forcing). Typical new minor forcing auctions are 1C-1S-1N-2D and 1D-1H-1N-2C. New minor forcing asks the opener about his or her major suit holdings. Opener should raise responder's original major suit with 3 card support, or bid a 4 card major (usually hearts).|
