I consider this lesson the single most important of the series. If you learn and apply the principles presented here, your bidding will improve, even if you do not take any of the subsequent lessons. I am focusing on what is known as "constructive bidding" because that will make it somewhat easier to explain. Constructive bidding is bidding when the opponents do not interfere. I will also ignore slam bidding for these lessons for simplicity. Even if you are not good at slam bidding, you can still be a very good bidder, because slams are rather rare. Now, let's talk about the 2 simple objectives of every constructive auction. They are:|
PG| ***** 164 ***** |


AT|
 
1) bid game if possible; if you don't have game, stay as low as you can
2) Find a good strain (that means a suit or NT). This lesson is about objective (1)--how to figure out if you have game. Objective (2) will be covered in subsequent lessons.|
PG| ***** 165 ***** |


AT|
 
In these lessons, I am assuming everyone is familiar with basic hand evaluation. By that I mean the 4-3-2-1 system of counting high card points and that you make some small adjustments for distribution. I use the classic 1 point for doubleton, 2  points for a singleton, 3 points for a void. Some people prefer length--1 point for each card in a suit over 4 cards (1 point for 5 card suit, 2 for six card, etc). You can use either (but not both)! I will explain in Kia's movie why I think shortness is slightly better. Now, most of you know I really like Bergen's hand evaluation methods. But, because not everyone knows them, I will stick with the simple hand evaluation that most people know.|
