The other main way to describe a medium hand is to "reverse." Many less experienced players find reverses very confusing and they can be. However, they are very important so you should learn about them if you can. Otherwise, whenever you have a medium hand and cannot open 1N, you will have a big problem. The good news is, I think I can give you a reasonably simple rule for how you figure out if opener has reversed. The rule is as follows: If opener voluntarily passes by his or her original suit at the 2 level in order to bid a new suit that is a reverse. For example, take the auction 1@D-1@S-2@H. 2@H is a reverse. Opener had the opportunity to bid 2@D and chose not to do so. Therefore, opener is showing a medium or maximum hand because of the reverse. Some beginners will make the 2@H bid with a minimum hand, just to show their major. That is incorrect. If opener reverses, he or she must have at least a medium hand. Playing reverses does mean once in a while you lose the heart suit. But the advantages of reversing correctly far outweigh the disadvantages.|
